  "prompt": "How do I connect my PC's internet to my Windows Phone via USB or via Bluetooth?",
  "response": "## Sharing your PC's Internet Connection with a Windows Phone\n\nUnfortunately, modern Windows Phones (those running Windows 10 Mobile or later) **do not support USB tethering or Bluetooth tethering** to share a PC's internet connection. This feature was removed in newer Windows Phone operating systems.\n\n**Therefore, you *cannot* directly connect your PC's internet to your Windows Phone via USB or Bluetooth.**\n\n**Alternative Solutions (Depending on your situation):**\n\n1. **Wi-Fi Hotspot:**\n\n   *   **Easiest and most common method.**\n   *   **PC Setup (Windows 10/11):**\n        *   Go to **Settings** (Windows key + I).\n        *   Click on **Network & Internet**.\n        *   Select **Mobile hotspot**.\n        *   Toggle the \"Mobile hotspot\" switch to **On**.\n        *   Under \"Share my Internet connection from,\" choose the connection your PC uses (e.g., Wi-Fi adapter if connected to Wi-Fi, Ethernet if connected via Ethernet cable).\n        *   Set a **network name (SSID)** and **password**.\n   *   **Windows Phone Setup:**\n        *   On your Windows Phone, go to **Settings**.\n        *   Select **Wi-Fi**.\n        *   Turn on **Wi-Fi**.\n        *   Find the Wi-Fi network you created on your PC (the SSID) and connect to it using the password you set.\n\n2. **Wi-Fi Router:**\n\n   *   If possible, connect both your PC and Windows Phone to the same Wi-Fi network provided by a Wi-Fi router. This is the most typical and stable solution.\n\n3. **Mobile Data:**\n\n   *   If your Windows Phone has a SIM card and a data plan, use its mobile data connection directly.\n\n**Why USB/Bluetooth Tethering is Gone:**\n\nMicrosoft likely removed these features due to a combination of factors:\n\n*   **Decreased Usage:** Wi-Fi hotspots and mobile data became much more common.\n*   **Driver Complexity:** Maintaining drivers and compatibility for USB/Bluetooth tethering across various PC configurations can be challenging.\n*   **OS Architecture:** Architectural changes in Windows 10 Mobile may have made tethering more difficult to implement.\n*   **End of Life:**  Microsoft has effectively ended support for Windows Phone, meaning they are not actively developing or updating the OS to include features like tethering.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Driver Issues:** Even on older Windows Phones, USB/Bluetooth tethering could be unreliable if the correct drivers were not installed on your PC.\n*   **Battery Drain:** USB tethering can drain your phone's battery, as it's constantly charging and providing a network connection. Bluetooth tethering typically drains battery slower but provides slower speeds.\n*   **Security:** Always use a strong password for your Wi-Fi hotspot to prevent unauthorized access.\n\nIn conclusion, using a Wi-Fi hotspot from your PC is the most practical way to share your internet connection with a Windows Phone since USB and Bluetooth tethering are no longer supported.\n",
